* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1941|08|09|df=y}} |event= [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] and [[Winston Churchill]] meet at [[Naval Station Argentia|NS Argentia]], [[Dominion of Newfoundland|Newfoundland]]. The [[Atlantic Charter]] is written and released to the world press. }}

=== December ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1941|12|07|df=y}} |event= Japan attacks the US Navy base of [[Pearl Harbor]] in Hawaii. Churchill was with the President's special envoy, Averell Harriman, and the US Ambassador to Britain, John Gilbert Winant, when he received the news over the telephone from President Roosevelt.<ref name="loc">{{cite web|title=Churchill and the Great Republic|url=https://www.loc.gov/exhibits/churchill/wc-sword.html|website=Library of Congress|accessdate=1 February 2016}}</ref>}}
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1941|12|08|df=y}} |end-date={{End date|1941|12|15|df=y}} |event=Japan attacks Hong Kong, Malaya and the Philippines in a simultaneous attack with Pearl Harbor but is counted a day later due to the [[international date line]].<ref name="bbc">{{cite web|last1=Robinson|first1=Bruce|title=World War Two: Summary Outline of Key Events|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/worldwars/wwtwo/ww2_summary_01.shtml#three|website=BBC History|accessdate=1 February 2016}}</ref>}}
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1941|12|10|df=y}} |event= Japanese air forces [[Sinking of Prince of Wales and Repulse|sink]] the ''Prince of Wales'' and ''Repulse''.}} 
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1941|12|26|df=y}} |event= Churchill makes his first address to a joint session of the United States Congress.}}<ref name="loc"/>
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1941|12|26|df=y}} |event= The evening after speaking to Congress, Churchill suffers a mild heart attack.}}<ref name="loc"/>

== 1942 ==
[[File:Sir Winston S Churchill.jpg|thumb|[[Churchill]] (1942)]]

===February===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1942|02|15|df=y}} |event= The Commonwealth forces at Singapore [[Battle of Singapore|surrender]] to the Japanese.}}

=== April ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1942|04|14|df=y}} |event= [[Winston Churchill|Churchill]], concerned that the situation in Malta will cause the Axis forces in North Africa to be better supplied than British forces, sends a telegram to [[Sir Stafford Cripps]] in Cairo, asking him to pressure [[Claude Auchinleck|General Auchinleck]] to take offensive action before this can occur.}}
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1942|04|20|df=y}} |event= [[William Dobbie|General Dobbie]], Governor-General and Commander-in-Chief of [[Malta]], sends a message to [[Winston Churchill|the PM]] saying "it is obvious that the very worst may happen if we cannot replenish our vital needs, especially flour and ammunition, and that very soon...." Churchill concludes from this and other "disturbing news" that Dobbie is not capable enough for such an important job, and decides to replace him with [[Lord Gort]].}}

=== May ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1942|05|09|df=y}} |event= On the night of 8-9 May 1942, gunners of the [[Ceylon Garrison Artillery]] on Horsburgh Island in the Cocos Islands rebelled. Their mutiny was crushed and three of them were executed, the only British Commonwealth soldiers to be executed for mutiny during the Second World War.<br>USS Wasp and HMS Eagle deliver a second contingent of Spitfires to Malta in [[Operation Bowery]]. A few days later, a grateful Churchill will signal Wasp "Who says a Wasp can't sting twice?" These aircraft, employed more aggressively than those previously delivered, turn the tide in the skies over Malta during the next few days, and the Axis is forced to abandon daylight bombing. This is a major turning point in the Siege, and thus in the North African Campaign, although the approaches to the island remain subject to deadly and accurate Axis air attack, preventing efficient re-supply of the island.}}
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1942|05|10|df=y}} |event=10: Churchill, growing ever more frustrated with [[General Auchinleck]]'s inactivity, finally sends him a telegram with a clear order; attack in time to cover for the Harpoon/Vigorous convoys to Malta during the dark of the moon in early June. This places Auchinleck in the position of complying or resigning. Auchinleck does not immediately reply, leaving Churchill, CIGS, and the War Cabinet in a state of suspense.}}
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1942|05|17|df=y}} |event= It has been a week since Churchill sent his ultimatum to [[General Auchinleck]], and he has not yet received a reply. He sends a terse follow-up: "It is necessary for me to have some account of your general intentions in light of our recent telegrams." Again there is no immediate reply. }}
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1942|05|19|df=y}} |event= [[General Auchinleck]] at last replies to Churchill's somewhat urgent telegram of the 10th, saying he will have an attack ready by the sailing of the Harpoon/Vigorous convoys for Malta.}}
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1942|05|21|df=y}} |event= In discussions with Winston Churchill and [[Anthony Eden]], Molotov continues to press Soviet demands for territorial acquisitions made during the run-up to war, including the Baltic states, Eastern Poland, and Bessarabia. Churchill cannot or will not agree to these demands, and the talks become deadlocked.}}

=== June ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1942|06|14|df=y}} |event= At the [[Gazala Line]], the British position has become untenable, and General Auchinleck authorizes General Ritchie to make a concerted withdrawal from forward positions along the line. <br> 1st South African Division is able to withdraw along the coastal road, but the road cannot accommodate all the troops at once, and this route in any event is under threat of being cut by [[Rommel]]'s forces; so troops including 50th Division must first breakout to the southwest, through the area occupied by Italian X Corps, and then turn east to rejoin 8th Army. This somewhat daring operation is concluded successfully. The RAF forces available, although outnumbered, make a valiant effort to cover the retreat. Churchill sends [[General Auchinleck|Auchinleck]] a telegram beginning, 'To what position does Ritchie want to withdraw the Gazala troops? Presume there is no question in any case of giving up Tobruk.' <br> The convoy 'Vigorous', en route to Malta, sights a large Italian naval squadron headed toward it. 'Harpoon' comes under attack for the first time; 'Vigorous' has been under air attack almost since leaving port. }}
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1942|06|15|df=y}} |event = [[General Auchinleck]] sends Churchill a reply to the latter's telegram of the 14th, saying in part, "...I have no intention whatever of giving up Tobruk." }}
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1942|06|16|df=y}} |event= Churchill, about to leave for America, takes the unusual step of sending a letter to HRM George VI, advising him to make Anthony Eden Prime Minister should Churchill not survive the journey.}}
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1942|06|18|df=y}} |event= Winston Churchill arrives in Washington for meetings with Roosevelt.}}

=== July ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1942|07|02|df=y}} |event= Churchill survives a censure motion in the House of Commons.}}

=== August ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1942|08|12|df=y}} |event= At a conference in Moscow, Churchill informs [[Stalin]] that there will not be a "second front" in 1942.}}
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1942|08|13|df=y}} |event= General Bernard Montgomery appointed commander of British Eighth Army in North Africa; Churchill is anxious to see more offensive action on the part of the British.}}

=== November ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1942|11|10|df=y}} |event= Montgomery begins a major British offensive beginning at Sollum on the Libya/Egypt border. The British reach [[Bardia]] on the 11th, [[Tobruk]] on the 12th, and [[Benghazi]] on the 18th. <br> Lieutenant [[General Montgomery]] is knighted and made a full General. Churchill speaks: "This is not the end. It is not even the beginning of the end. But it is, perhaps, the end of the beginning."}}

=== December ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1942|12|17|df=y}} |event= From the floor of the House of Commons, Foreign Secretary Anthony Eden reads what is known as the [[Joint Declaration by Members of the United Nations]], in which the Allies denounce the German extermination of Jews. A copy of the declaration appears on the front pages of newspapers around the world.}}<ref name="bbc2">{{cite web|title=BBC On This Day: 17 December 1942|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/december/17/newsid_3547000/3547151.stm|accessdate=1 February 2016}}</ref>

== 1943 ==
[[File:Churchill V sign HU 55521.jpg|thumb|[[Churchill]] (1943)]]
[[Image:Teheran conference-1943.jpg|thumb|[[Tehran conference]] (1943). Left to right: [[Joseph Stalin]], [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] of the [[United States]], and [[Churchill]]]]

=== January ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1943|01|14|df=y}} |event= The [[Casablanca Conference]] of Allied leaders begins. [[Winston Churchill]] and [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] discuss the eventual invasion of mainland Europe, the impending invasion of Sicily and Italy, and the wisdom of the principle of "unconditional surrender".}}

=== May ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1943|05|12|df=y}} |event= The [[Washington Conference (1943)|Trident Conference]] begins in [[Washington, D.C.]] with Franklin D. Roosevelt and Winston Churchill taking part. The discussions are mostly on future strategy.<ref name="ww2db">{{cite web|url=http://ww2db.com/event/timeline/1943/ |title=1943 Timeline |publisher=WW2DB |accessdate=2013-01-07}}</ref><ref name="etherington">{{cite web |url=http://homepage.ntlworld.com/andrew.etherington/frame.htm |title=Chronology of World War Two |publisher=andrew.etherington |accessdate=2013-01-07 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026052603/http://homepage.ntlworld.com/andrew.etherington/frame.htm |archivedate=2012-10-26 |df= }}</ref>}}
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1943|05|19|df=y}} |event= [[Winston Churchill]] addresses a joint session of the [[U.S. Congress]]. He praises the partnership of the two Allies.}}<ref name="etherington"/>

=== July ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1943|07|25|df=y}} |event= [[Benito Mussolini]] is removed from office; it leads to the formation of a new government in Italy.}}

=== August ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1943|08|19|df=y}} |event= Roosevelt and Churchill signed the [[Quebec Agreement]] during the [[Quebec Conference, 1943|Quebec Conference]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://avalon.law.yale.edu/wwii/q002.asp |title=Avalon Project - The Quebec Conference - Agreement Relating to Atomic Energy|publisher=yale.edu|accessdate=2013-07-18}}</ref>}}

=== October ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1943|10|03|df=y}} |event= Churchill appoints [[Louis Mountbatten, 1st Earl Mountbatten of Burma|Lord Louis Mountbatten]] the commander of [[South-East Asian theatre of World War II#Allied command structure|South East Asia Command]].}}

=== November ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1943|11|16|df=y}} |event= 160 [[United States|American]] bombers strike a [[hydro-electric power]] facility and [[heavy water]] factory in [[Germany|German]]-controlled [[Vemork]], [[Norway]].}}
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1943|11|22|df=y}} |event= The [[Cairo Conference (1943)|Cairo Conference]]: US President [[Franklin Delano Roosevelt|Franklin D. Roosevelt]], British Prime Minister [[Winston Churchill]], and ROC leader [[Chiang Kai-shek]] meet in [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]], to discuss ways to defeat [[Japan]].}}
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1943|11|27|df=y}} |event= The Cairo Conference ("Sextant") ends; Roosevelt, Churchill, and [[Chiang Kai-shek]] complete the [[1943 Cairo Declaration|Cairo Declaration]], which deals with the overall strategic plan against Japan.}}
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1943|11|28|df=y}} |event= The [[Tehran Conference]].  US President [[Franklin Delano Roosevelt|Franklin D. Roosevelt]], British Prime Minister [[Winston Churchill]] and Soviet Leader [[Joseph Stalin]] meet in [[Tehran]] to discuss war strategy; (on 30 November they establish an agreement concerning a planned June 1944 invasion of Europe codenamed [[Operation Overlord]]). Stalin at last has the promise he has been waiting for.}}

== 1944 ==
[[File:Churchill HU 90973.jpg|thumb|[[Churchill]] (1944)]]

=== February ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1944|02|10|df=y}} |event= [[Winston Churchill]] urges [[Harold Alexander]] to order the Anzio generals to show more aggression.<ref name="ww2db1944">{{cite web|url=http://ww2db.com/event/timeline/1944/ |title=1944 Timeline |publisher=WW2DB |accessdate=2014-02-19}}</ref>}}

=== June ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date |1944|06|06|df=y}} |event=British and US troops land at Normandy in France, initiating a [[Western Front (World War II)#1944.E2.80.9345: The Second Front|Second Front]] against Germany. Codenamed [[Operation Overlord]], the day is also known as D-Day.}}

=== August ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date |1944|08|20|df=y}} |event=Allied troops reach Paris.}}

=== September ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1944|09|12|df=y}} |event= The [[Second Quebec Conference]] (codenamed "Octagon") begins: Roosevelt and Churchill discuss military cooperation in the Pacific and the future of Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/ww2peopleswar/timeline/factfiles/nonflash/a1144838.shtml?sectionId=6&articleId=1144838 |title=BBC - WW2 People's War - Timeline|publisher=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=2014-09-11}}</ref>}}

=== October ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1944|10|09|df=y}} |event= The [[Moscow Conference (1944)]] begins: Churchill and [[Stalin]] discuss spheres of influence in the postwar Balkans and make the [[percentages agreement]].}}

=== December ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1944|12|03|df=y}} |event= The British army and the police shot unarmed protesters in Athens. The crowd carried Greek, American, British and Soviet flags, and chanted: "Viva Churchill, Viva Roosevelt, Viva Stalin." <!-- Commented out: [[File:Dekemvriana 1944 SYNTAGMA.jpg|thumbnail|The unarmed crowd carried Greek, American, British and Soviet flags in Athens, the British army and the police killed 28 civilians and hundreds injured]] -->}}
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1944|12|16|df=y}} |event=[[Battle of the Bulge]] begins.}}
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1944|12|28|df=y}} |event=:28: Churchill and his Foreign Secretary [[Anthony Eden]] are in Athens in an attempt to reconcile the warring factions.
}}

== 1945 ==
[[File:Churchill waves to crowds.jpg|thumb|[[Churchill]] waves to crowds in Whitehall on the day he broadcast to the nation that the war with Germany had been won, 8 May 1945]]

=== February ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1945|02|04|df=y}} |event= The [[Yalta Conference]] of Roosevelt, [[Winston Churchill]] and [[Joseph Stalin]] begins;<ref name="etherington"/><ref name="1945 Timeline">{{cite web|url=http://ww2db.com/event/timeline/1945/ |title=1945 Timeline |publisher=WW2DB |accessdate=2011-02-09}}</ref> the main subject of their discussions is postwar spheres of influence. }}

=== April ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date |1945|04|12|df=y}} |event=US President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] dies, and is succeeded by Vice President [[Harry S Truman]].}} 
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1945|04|16|df=y}} |event=The Soviets overtake Berlin.}} 
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1945|04|30|df=y}} |event=Hitler commits suicide, is succeeded by [[Karl Doenitz]].}}

=== May ===
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1945|05|07|df=y}} |event=Germany surrenders to the western Allies.}}
* 23 May 1945: Wartime coalition ends. Start of brief [[Churchill caretaker ministry|caretaker government.]]

===June===
*5 June 1945:  The longest parliament of the 20th century is dissolved.

=== July ===
[[Image:L to R, British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, President Harry S. Truman, and Soviet leader Josef Stalin in the... - NARA - 198958.jpg|thumb|left|At the end: [[Winston Churchill]], [[Harry S. Truman]], and [[Joseph Stalin]]]]
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1945|07|17|df=y}} |event= The [[Potsdam Conference]] begins under Churchill (later replaced by [[Clement Attlee|Attlee]]), [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]] and [[Harry S. Truman|Truman]]. The Allied leaders agree to insist upon the [[unconditional surrender]] of Japan, which takes place on 9 August 1945.}}
* {{Timeline-event |date={{Start date|1945|07|26|df=y}} |event= The [[British Labour Party|Labour Party]] win the [[United Kingdom general election, 1945|United Kingdom general election]] by a landslide. Churchill resigns as Prime Minister, ending his first premiership.}}
